details: STAFF PICK!It’s hard to find a good wine to bring to dinner parties. What are the hosts cooking? What are others bringing? What wine goes with what? Do wine pairings matter at all? Lucky for you, we have the answer. Beaujolais! Beaujolais, made of the grape gamay, is a cheat code for the dinner table. We love Beaujolais and try to stock our shelves with as many as possible.This particular wine is from Chiroubles, one of the ten Crus of Beaujolais. Chiroubles has vineyards with some of the highest altitudes in Beaujolais, which gives the wine cheerful, bright acidity, perfect for most foods. The Chiroubles 2018 La Grosse Pierre also exhibits a savory, deeper profile, which is great for richer, fuller meals. Drink with a chill!––Graham VK

name: Toscana Rosso 2016 3L Massoferrato
description: Sangiovese of your dreams, in the size of your dreams. Dream big.
details: STAFF PICK!So you need a lot of wine for not so much money? Large format wine options extend beyond the bottles of magnums and jeroboams popular in the city’s hottest restaurants. If you trust your wine store (which you totally do), consider the humble bag-in-box option, an environmentally friendly marvel that keeps 3 liters of wine aka, 4 bottles, fresh for a few weeks after you open it. Specifically consider this Massoferrato Toscana which is 100% Sangiovese, the grape you know and love from Chianti. This stuff comes from Emilia-Romagna, which is a little northeast of Tuscany. It’s dry and sturdy with a nice aroma of cherry and a little savory edge. The first day you open it the wine might be a little tight, but my advice for this and all boxed wines is to decant from the box into a carafe before service. Not only does it class things up, but it gives the wine a chance to breathe a little as well. –Tammie

name: Garnacha Volandera 2018 La Calandria
description: Strawberries and wild mountain thyme. Enjoy with almost anything.
details: STAFF PICK!We carry many bottles of Garnacha, as well as Garnacha blends, so when we choose to bring in a new one, it really is crucial that it WOWs us. The most basic quality of this common grape is that it’s always gonna taste big and juicy. Not only does the Volandera rise to the expectation we are all looking for with that textbook Garnacha flavor, but it also soars to a whole new level of lip-smacking late-night goodness. Completely ignoring the unique design of the bottle, this deep, fruity red wine is bound to stand up and stand out during any of these (highly anticipated!) chilly October nights.–Jake

details: STAFF PICK!We are entering colder weather (in theory), it’s time to ease our way into something a little cozier… Cabernet franc from Bourgueil is a bold, often gritty and austere, wine that should compliment the soon-to-be changing foliage and brisk air. This is a wine with chutzpah, somewhat sweaty and salty, with light aromas of roasted bell pepper. While relatively dense, the wine balances its graphite-y profile with lovely tannin and acid. Would kill with any red or gamey meat, or even just alone, on your couch, with good company (oneself can also be considered good company, if not great). Enjoy.–Graham
